  1. In your own words, what does

, facets = . ~ Species)

mean in a qplot() call?

In a qplot() call, the above code tells R that we are splitting the plot into several panels based on the variable Species. The tilde (~) separates rows (left side) and columns (right side) in the facet layout. The dot (.) means dont split in that direction. Putting Species on the right means make separate columns for each Species.

  1. You just spent some time learning qplot(), but youll likely never use it. Youll use ggplot2 from now on. What are the seven basic components of ggplot2 plots?

The seven basic components of a ggplot2 plot are:

  • Data the dataset you want to visualize. (i.e.iris like we did above)

  • Aesthetics (aes) how variables are mapped to visual properties (like x and y axis, color, size).

  • Geometries (geoms) the type of plot elements (points, lines, bars, etc.).

  • Facets optional panels that split data into multiple plots based on variables (could be columns or rows).

  • Statistics (stats) optional transformations or summaries of data (like smoothing lines or counts).

  • Coordinates (coords) how data are positioned on the plot (like Cartesian or polar coordinates).

  • Theme overall look and style of the plot (background, fonts, gridlines, etc.).

  1. Make a ggplot object with the mapping: x = ~Sepal.Length, y = ~Sepal.Width. Then make a scatterplot with regression lines separated by Species, with the plot title Swirl Rules!. Paste the command and the plot here.
# Creating ggplot object with requested mapping 
ggplot(iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width, color = Species)) +
  # Telling R that it's meant to be a scatterplot
  geom_point() +
  # Adding regression lines to the plot
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) +
  # Adding labels, including title and axis
  labs(title = "Swirl Rules!",
       x = "Sepal Length",
       y = "Sepal Width") +
  theme_minimal()

  1. Using qplot, make a histogram of Sepal.Length from data = iris. Paste the command and the plot here. Next, using qplot make a density plot of Sepal.Length from data = iris. Paste the command and plot below the histogram. Please answer what the different plots tell you (i.e., what is the difference between a frequency histogram and a probability density function?).
# Histogram of Sepal.Length
qplot(Sepal.Length, data = iris, bins = 20, main = "Histogram of Sepal.Length")

# Density plot of Sepal.Length
qplot(Sepal.Length, data = iris, geom = "density", main = "Density Plot of Sepal.Length")

The histogram tells us how many of something (in this case flowers) occurs in each range (of length, in this case). The density plot tells us how likely a value is to occur (probability distribution of sepal lengths in this case), emphasizing the shape of the distribution rather than counts. In the histogram, the height of each bar represents how many data points are in that range. Its discrete and depends on bin width. In the density plot, the area under the curve equals 1, not the total number of observations. It provides a smoothed view of the distributions shape.
